Subject:Re: [Antenna-discussion] RF noise
Stu
I quite agree with you and the problem lies in the need for economic
growth at all costs, coupled with the relative unimportance of radio
comms in the modern world - especially hf, now that we are all wired
up.  So the 'authorities' don't see noise on HF as one of the big
problems.  I think the services use hf radio still, but they can place
antenna farms away from noise sources, where they can still enjoy a
quiet spectrum.  The rest of us have data on our copper-wire phone
lines and our power system, plus endless loud noise from anything with
a switch-mode power supply in it, which means just about everything
these days :(
Alan G3NOQ


On 17 October 2012 09:23, Stu Nutt <stunutt@gmail.com> wrote:
> That's one of my next jobs - I've just (almost) finished building a new
> shack in the garden (with a bit of solar power, and some solar heating), but
> my small wooden lattice tower had to come down as it was in the only place
> the shack could go, so now I only have a v/uhf vertical and a 10m vertical
> available - I need to work out where to re-site the tower and put it up!
>
> I think I can rule out the "change in RX design", as my 1990's (or maybe
> even '80's) era TS150 is no better than the 857 in terms of received noise;
> I'm pretty convinced that it's mostly the "consumer electronics".  Here in
> UK, our equivalent of the FCC seems to be under-staffed and not effectively
> controlling the emissions from a lot of imported equipment; our RSGB (radio
> society - like ARRL) seems to be permanently up against them over
> internet-over-power systems that are supposed to be "notched" so as to not
> interfere with ham bands and other low-signal applications, but has
> frequently been measured (by the society) at well above these so-called
> limits.
>
> [RANT OFF] !
>
> Stu
