> On 17/10/2012 05:19, Augie "Gus" Hansen wrote:
>>
>> Hi Stu,
>>
>> Sorry about the delayed response. I've been busy upgrading my antennas and
>> shack solar power system. After all that roof and tower work it feels good
>> to have my feet back on the ground.
>>
>> In addition to electrical storms, here are just a few other possible
>> factors:
>>
>> - Receiver technology changes (analog vs digital, for example).
>> - AGC characteristics and gain distribution affect perceived S+N/N.
>> - Increasing man-made noise sources from poorly implemented consumer
>> electronics.
>> - Aging power distribution infrastructure (my worst noise problem).
>>
>>
>> I'm not making any claims, simply pointing to a meteorologist's estimate
>> of the number of lightning strikes per day worldwide.
>>
>> Climate changes occur over time, driven by short-, medium-, and long-cycle
>> phenomena, mostly related to the sun. I don't know whether the frequency or
>> severity of storms have increased since I was a youngster in the 1950s in
>> Rhode Island, but I assume that there have been fluctuations.
>>
>> Gus Hansen
>> KB0YH
